\textbf{Question:}

A group of friends are sharing some pieces of cake at a picnic. There are 3 pieces of cake, and together they make up \( \frac{3}{4} \) of a whole cake. The friends want to divide these 3 pieces equally among 6 people.

\begin{enumerate}
    \item What fraction of a whole cake does each person get?
    \item Explain your answer using the idea of dividing a set of pieces.
\end{enumerate}

response_dict.solution:
\textbf{Solution:}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Since 3 pieces represent \( \frac{3}{4} \) of a whole cake, dividing these 3 pieces equally among 6 people is the same as dividing \( \frac{3}{4} \) by 6:
    \[
    \frac{3}{4} \div 6 = \frac{3}{4} \times \frac{1}{6} = \frac{3}{24} = \frac{1}{8}
    \]
    So, each person gets \( \frac{1}{8} \) of a whole cake.

    \item The 3 pieces (making up \( \frac{3}{4} \) of a whole cake) are considered as a set. Sharing these 3 pieces among 6 people means each person receives 1 out of every 2 pieces (since 6 is twice 3). If we imagine the cake is cut into 4 equal parts, taking 3 of them and sharing equally among 6 people means each person receives half of one piece, or \( \frac{1}{8} \) of the whole set.
\end{enumerate}

